Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[According to article 2.3.13 of OIE's Terrestrial
Animal Health Code, member countries can be
regarded to have one of the 2 categories
"Negligible BSE risk" or "Controlled BSE risk"
provided they fulfilled the requirements detailed
in articles 2.3.13.3. and 2.3.13.4.,
respectively. If it cannot be demonstrated that
the country meets the requirements of one of the
said categories, the country is regarded to be of
"Undetermined BSE risk". The code addresses the
import requirements of animals and animal
products from such countries. Obviously, the
risks related to imports from countries with
'Undetermined BSE Risk' status are higher than
from countries of the other categories, and
accordingly import requirements from them may be
more demanding. For the detailed category
requirements and their respective international trade conditions, see
<http://oie.int/eng/normes/mcode/en_chapitre_2.3.13.htm#article_2.3.13.2>.

During its 75th General Session, Paris, 22 May
2007, OIE's International Committee endorsed
Resolution No. XXIV "Recognition of the Bovine
Spongiform Encephalopathy Status of Member Countries"
(<http://www.oie.int/eng/info/en_statesb.htm?e1d6#Reso>).
According to the said resolution, Australia,
Argentina, New Zealand, Singapore and Uruguay
were recognised as countries with a 'negligible BSE risk.'

The following countries were recognised as
countries with a 'controlled BSE risk:' Brazil,
Canada, Chile, Switzerland, Taipei China and
United States of America. Iceland and Paraguay
were recognised as 'provisionally free' from BSE
in accordance with Chapter 2.3.13. of the Code
and Resolution XXVII of the 74th General Session,
to remain on the list published by the OIE until May 2008.

Later, 2 meetings of the OIE AD HOC GROUP FOR
EVALUATION OF COUNTRY STATUS FOR BSE IN
ACCORDANCE WITH THE TERRESTRIAL ANIMAL HEALTH
CODE were held in Paris, namely on 16­-20 July
2007 and 12­-14 September 2007. The following
countries have been recognised to belong to the
category "Negligible BSE risk": Finland, Iceland,
Norway and Sweden. The following countries were
found to have "Controlled BSE risk": Austria,
Belgium, Cyprus, Czech Republic, Denmark,
Estonia, France, Germany, Greece, Hungary,
Ireland, Italy, Latvia, Lithuania, Luxembourg,
Malta, Netherlands, Poland, Portugal, Slovak
Republic, Slovenia, Spain and the United Kingdom.

The Group assessed 2 additional country dossiers which did not meet
the requirements, neither for 'negligible BSE risk' nor for
'controlled BSE risk.' These dossiers were referred back to the
corresponding countries.

For the detailed discussions on each of the applicants, subscribers
are referred to appendix VII (pages 55-108) of the REPORT OF THE
MEETING OF THE OIE SCIENTIFIC COMMISSION FOR ANIMAL DISEASES, Paris,
18 - 20 Sep 2007, available at
<http://www.oie.int/downld/SC/2007/A_SCAD_Sept2007.pdf>. - Mod. AS]
